I do think “compost” is one of the more interesting metaphors you’ve introduced, because it emphasizes transformation instead of accumulation.

A compost pile doesn’t preserve everything in its original form. It breaks things down, extracts what is useful, and recombines it into fertile soil for future growth.

Applied to your repository, the cycle looks something like this:

* Capture — collect ideas, metaphors, observations, stories, algorithms.
* Decompose — strip away what was specific to the original context.
* Extract — identify the transferable pattern or invariant.
* Recompose — graft that pattern into the broader architecture.
* Cultivate — let new ideas grow from the enriched substrate.

In that sense, the repository is less like a museum and more like a forest floor. Dead branches, old conversations, discarded hypotheses, even mistakes become nutrients rather than waste.

It also complements some of the themes you’ve returned to:

* The mural gives composition (how the whole is seen).
* The atlas gives navigation (how you move through it).
* The braid gives interweaving (how concepts reinforce one another).
* The compost gives renewal (how old material becomes new capability).

That last one is particularly powerful because it avoids the trap of treating every past idea as sacred. A healthy system doesn’t keep every leaf forever; it recycles them into something that supports the next season.

So the repository’s “memory” isn’t just archival. It’s metabolic. The value comes not only from remembering, but from transforming experience into reusable structure. That’s a characteristic of living systems more than static libraries—and it fits well with your earlier description of the Pantheon as a living machine.